%% Finding Lifecycle — how one candidate FindingRecord moves from mapped
%% technique to a persisted, deduplicated Finding row, and how a matching
%% candidate merges into an existing open Finding rather than duplicating it
%% (constitution §1.7; docs/adr/0013-finding-mitre-intelligence-engine-shape.md).
%% Render with `mmdc -i finding-lifecycle.mmd -o finding-lifecycle.png`.

stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Mapped: MitreMappingEngine matches >=1 rule\n(one candidate per mapped technique_id)
    Mapped --> Unmapped: no rule matched or confidence <\nfinding_mapping_min_confidence
    Unmapped --> [*]: no Finding generated\n(never a forced low-confidence guess)

    Mapped --> Aggregated: EvidenceAggregator.aggregate()\n[timeline, chain of custody, affected assets]
    Aggregated --> Scored: ConfidenceEngine.calculate()\n[7 dimensions -> composite]
    Scored --> Prioritized: assign_severity() / assign_priority() /\ncalculate_risk_score()
    Prioritized --> Deduplicated: FindingDeduplicationEngine.evaluate()\nagainst this case's OPEN Findings

    Deduplicated --> Open: decision=NEW\nFinding + FindingMitreMapping rows inserted
    Deduplicated --> Merged: decision=MERGE (similarity >= threshold)\nmerge_findings() unions evidence/IOCs/mappings

    Open --> Closed: analyst/future IR Agent closes the case
    Closed --> Merged: a later run's candidate merges into this\nFinding — merge_findings() reopens it (new\nevidence is grounds to reconsider a closed decision)

    Open --> [*]
    Closed --> [*]
    Merged --> [*]

    note right of Deduplicated
        Six dimensions, bucket-first (not naive
        pairwise): hash similarity, IOC overlap,
        technique overlap, evidence overlap,
        time-window proximity, host overlap.
        Two Findings mapped to disjoint technique
        sets are never merge candidates, however
        much supporting evidence otherwise overlaps
        (one-IOC-to-many-techniques stays separate).
    end note

    note right of Mapped
        Scoped to *within* one case's Findings —
        never cross-case correlation (explicit
        scope cut, docs/adr/0013 "Scope Cuts").
    end note
